<paragraph blockId="9.[498,1530,1542,1849]" box="[498,612,1542,1569]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<heading bold="true" box="[498,612,1542,1569]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" reason="0">Diagnosis</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[498,1530,1542,1849]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Body is fungiform, pedunculate, basiphytous with a more-or-less everted atrial cavity. Choanosomal spicules predominantly diactins, rarely hexactins and pentactins too. The spicules of the peduncle are diactins fused into a rigid skeleton by synapticular junctions. Dermalia and atrialia are hexactins, rarely pentactins. Microscleres are anchorate and toothed discohexasters, discasters, hemidiscohexasters, discohexactins, and derivatives of the latter to amphidiscs (
<bibRefCitation author="Tabachnick KR" box="[1023,1232,1782,1809]" editor="Hooper JNA &amp; Van Soest RWM" journalOrPublisher="New York: Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" pagination="1388 - 1434" refId="ref11475" refString="Tabachnick KR. 2002. Family Euplectellidae Gray, 1867. In: Hooper JNA, Van Soest RWM, eds. Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Vol. 2. New York: Kluwer Academic / Plenum Publishers, 1388 - 1434." title="Family Euplectellidae Gray" type="book chapter" volumeTitle="Systema Porifera: A guide to the classification of sponges. Vol. 2" year="2002">
<emphasis box="[1023,1232,1782,1809]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Tabachnick, 2002</emphasis>
</bibRefCitation>
